The paper deals with voting systems and their computational complexity in the face of control scenarios, which are typical topics in computational social choice (cs.GT) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The use of preference rankings and approval strategies also suggests a connection to machine learning (cs.LG) and multi-agent systems (cs.MA). Finally, the paper's focus on computational complexity and algorithmic analysis points to a possible connection to data structures and algorithms (cs.DS).
